Answer: \begin{blockquote}

Kanban and Scrum are two popular Agile frameworks used in software development, but there are some key differences between them.
\end{blockquote}

\begin{itemize}
\item \strong{Role-based vs. process-based:} Scrum is a role-based framework, which means that it defines specific roles for the team members, such as the Scrum Master, Product Owner, and Development Team. Kanban, on the other hand, is a process-based framework that doesn't define any specific roles.
\end{itemize}

\begin{blockquote}

\begin{itemize}
  \item Timeboxing vs. continuous flow: Scrum uses timeboxing, which means that work is organized into sprints, with a fixed duration (usually 2-4 weeks). Kanban, on the other hand, uses a continuous flow model, where work is pulled from a backlog as capacity allows, without any fixed timeboxes.

\end{itemize}
\end{blockquote}

\begin{itemize}
\item \strong{Prescriptive vs. flexible:} Scrum is more prescriptive than Kanban, as it provides a set of rules and ceremonies (such as sprint planning, daily stand-ups, sprint reviews, and retrospectives) that must be followed. Kanban, on the other hand, is more flexible and allows teams to define their own processes and ceremonies.
\end{itemize}

